05315nam a22006735i 9780824873950DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20052005hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248739507 a10.1515/97808248739502doi  a(DE-B1597)484592  a(OCoLC)1024024444  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aLAN0090002bisacsh0483pa400qDE-1011 aMaynard, Senko K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aExpressive Japanese :bA Reference Guide for Sharing Emotion and Empathy /cSenko K. Maynard. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (448 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tI. Introduction -- t1. On Expressive Japanese -- t2 .Expressive Japanese and the Characteristics of Japanese Discourse -- t3 .On Entries -- tII: Emotion -- t4. When Deeply Moved -- t5. Experiencing Emotion -- t6 .Emotionally Evaluating -- t7 .Responding to Circumstances Emotionally -- t8 .When Emotion Is Intense -- t9 .Falling in and out of Love -- t10. Emotion in Conflict Situations -- tIII :Empathy -- t11. Revealing Oneself Softly -- t12. Co-Experiencing Feelings -- t13. Appealing to Empathy and Amae -- t14. Designing Utterances for the Partner -- t15 .Concerned with Conversational Empathy -- t16 .Asserting Oneself Expressively and Being Creative -- tAppendix :Information about Authentic Sources -- tReferences -- tIndex of English Cues and Subject Index -- tIndex of Japanese Expressions0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFeelings play an enormous part in our lives, but their expression is often neglected in foreign language education. How do I communicate happiness, surprise, or anger? How do others communicate these emotions to me? Such questions become increasingly relevant as we become more competent in the language we are learning. Expressive Japanese is the first detailed guide to emotion words and expressive strategies for students of the language. Words connoting feelings, such as "kanashii" (sad), are important in everyday Japanese conversation, but communicating emotions effectively also requires the use of expressive strategies, such as "Nani?" (What the heck?), "Yattaa!" (I did it!), or "Hottoite!" (Leave me alone!). Introductory chapters examine the characteristics, constraints, and history of expressive Japanese and discuss linguistic variations and styles and how these play a part in conveying emotion and empathy. There follow more than seventy entries that draw on hundreds of authentic examples taken from a variety of sources, including television dramas, comics, interviews, novels, essays, newspaper articles, and web sites. In these examples, students will find playful and creative uses of expressions that do not usually appear in language textbooks. English cues and key Japanese expressions are indexed at the back of the volume, making this a handy reference for anyone who possesses a grasp of the fundamentals of elementary Japanese. Based on extensive research by a prominent linguist and teacher, Expressive Japanese brings learners into the world of real human interaction and effectively illustrates how native speakers use language to convey identity and a sense of self as well as to communicate feelings and emotion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Back